<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1577,2034]" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">
A portion of 
<emphasis box="[361,410,1794,1817]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">COI</emphasis>
gene was sequenced from our single specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Price &amp; Dalgleish" authorityYear="2006" box="[1022,1248,1793,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Menoponidae" genus="Myrsidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phthiraptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="violaceae">
<emphasis box="[1022,1248,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">Myrsidea violaceae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lesson" baseAuthorityYear="1832" class="Aves" family="Thraupidae" genus="Euphonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hirundinacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">Euphonia hirundinacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(GenBank accession number KY 
<date box="[684,770,1830,1854]" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" value="37-11-31">113137</date>
). Comparing our sequence with other known sequences of Neotropical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Literak" authorityYear="2017" box="[291,397,1865,1890]" class="Insecta" family="Menoponidae" genus="Myrsidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phthiraptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[291,397,1865,1890]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">Myrsidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the closest was that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Price &amp; Johnson, 2009" authorityName="Price &amp; Johnson" authorityYear="2009" box="[668,1113,1865,1890]" class="Insecta" family="Menoponidae" genus="Myrsidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phthiraptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rozsai">
<emphasis box="[668,849,1865,1890]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">Myrsidea rozsai</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Price" box="[856,1113,1865,1890]" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" refString="Price, R. D. &amp; Johnson, K. P. (2009) Five new species of Myrsidea Waterston (Phthiraptera: Menoponidae) from tanagers (Passeriformes: Thraupidae) in Panama. Zootaxa, 2200, 61 - 68." type="journal article" year="2009">Price &amp; Johnson, 2009</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName box="[1182,1436,1865,1890]" class="Aves" family="Thraupidae" genus="Euphonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lanniirostris">
<emphasis box="[1182,1436,1865,1890]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">Euphonia lanniirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(A/N FJ 
<date box="[248,335,1902,1926]" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" value="82-12-17">171282</date>
), with a sequence divergence of 11.9%. This divergence is on the border of the interspecific variation limit for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Literak" authorityYear="2017" box="[363,469,1937,1962]" class="Insecta" family="Menoponidae" genus="Myrsidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phthiraptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[363,469,1937,1962]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">Myrsidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species as proposed in this paper. More specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Literak" authorityYear="2017" box="[1098,1204,1937,1962]" class="Insecta" family="Menoponidae" genus="Myrsidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phthiraptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1098,1204,1937,1962]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">Myrsidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the above and other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desmarest" authorityYear="1806" box="[345,454,1973,1998]" class="Aves" family="Thraupidae" genus="Euphonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="173" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[345,454,1973,1998]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="173">Euphonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are needed to resolve the taxonomic status of these two nominal species, based on molecular and morphological data.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,151,284]" pageId="13" pageNumber="174">
Our specimen differs from descriptions of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Price &amp; Dalgleish" authorityYear="2006" box="[691,839,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Menoponidae" genus="Myrsidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phthiraptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="violaceae">
<emphasis box="[691,839,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="174">M. violaceae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by setal counts and dimensions, as follows (overall data from 
<bibRefCitation author="Price" box="[266,750,188,213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="174" refString="Price, R. D. &amp; Dalgleish, R. C. (2007) Myrsidea Waterston (Phthiraptera: Menoponidae) from the Emberizidae (Passeriformes), with descriptions of 13 new species. Zootaxa, 1467, 1 - 18." type="journal article" year="2007">
Price &amp; Dalgleish 2 0 0 6, Sychra 
<emphasis box="[628,684,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Kounek" box="[809,1022,188,213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="174" refString="Kounek, F., Sychra, O., Capek, M., Lipkova, A. &amp; Literak, I. (2011) Chewing lice of the genus Myrsidea (Phthiraptera: Menoponidae) from the Cardinalidae, Emberizidae, Fringillidae and Thraupidae (Aves: Passeriformes) from Costa Rica, with descriptions of four new species. Zootaxa, 3032, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="2011">
Kounek 
<emphasis box="[904,961,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
are in parentheses): 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,223,248]" pageId="13" pageNumber="174">Male</emphasis>
(n = 1). Tergal setae: VIII, 12 (14–18). Sternal setae: VIII+IX, 15 (7–14). Dimensions: POW, 0.31 (0.29– 0.30); TL, 1.23 (1.11–1.21).
</paragraph>
